<span id="freeTextContainer9673335366858409712">I don’t write reviews. <br/><br/>This is a strange little book. I read the description, but this isn’t a book where the description illuminates the reader. You must dive in. I felt the oddness in my bones. The characters aren’t “normal.” Are they human? Yes, yes, but are they more than.... no I’ll stop there. <br/><br/>The situations are interestingly complex. It was like looking into a miniature village in a snow globe or at a scene in a shadow box. Have you ever seen copper pennies made into tiny doll house furni</span>
  <span id="freeText9673335366858409712" style="display:none">I don’t write reviews. <br /><br />This is a strange little book. I read the description, but this isn’t a book where the description illuminates the reader. You must dive in. I felt the oddness in my bones. The characters aren’t “normal.” Are they human? Yes, yes, but are they more than.... no I’ll stop there. <br /><br />The situations are interestingly complex. It was like looking into a miniature village in a snow globe or at a scene in a shadow box. Have you ever seen copper pennies made into tiny doll house furniture? That’s this. <br /><br />I think Sturgeon did well carving out a little world for his misfits. Intriguing for sure. Part of the audiobook is narrated by a very old Harlan Elision. You won’t hear me complaining. </span>
