        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2980327490" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3098544436227506748">Sturgeon wrote &quot;Baby is Three&quot; (the middle part of this book) as a novella first. Later he expanded the beginning and ending chapter. All three parts read as novellas in themselves, different in tone and different in the protagonists. The original novella accompanied me since I was a teenager. &quot;Baby is Three&quot; was one of the first Sturgeon stories I&apos;ve read and it was life shaping for me in a certain sense. The idea of the homo gestalt was so different from what I had read since then, it spoke to</span>
  <span id="freeText3098544436227506748" style="display:none">Sturgeon wrote "Baby is Three" (the middle part of this book) as a novella first. Later he expanded the beginning and ending chapter. All three parts read as novellas in themselves, different in tone and different in the protagonists. The original novella accompanied me since I was a teenager. "Baby is Three" was one of the first Sturgeon stories I've read and it was life shaping for me in a certain sense. The idea of the homo gestalt was so different from what I had read since then, it spoke to me on a deep level, it made the strange outsider child that I was felt seen for the first time. <br />Sturgeon's psychological writing and exceptional command of prose expanded the genre of SF for me from spaceships and robots into a limitless possibility of human development. He showed me what SF could be, pushed it from pulp to literacy and got me addicted to this genre for the rest of my life. </span>
