    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_46935103" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/46935103" />
    <a title="Kirk" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2050288-kirk"><img alt="Kirk" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1476811824p2/2050288.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/46935103?book_show_action=true">Feb 19, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kirk" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kirk" href="/user/show/2050288-kirk">Kirk</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780345281890" href="/book/show/1003120.More_Than_Human">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2050288-kirk?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer46935103" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1563682171928857556">I end up seldom rereading books, I’m often tempted but then the guilt/panic kicks in of the reality of all the great books I haven’t even read once and I won’t even get to all those in one lifetime, so..…I almost always end up choosing a book I’ve never read. But occasionally the other voice in my head will insist, and (though not often) prevail. So here’s a reread of one of my formative science fiction novels, which blew my mind back in the day. And while I’m adjusting my rating to four stars (</span>
  <span id="freeText1563682171928857556" style="display:none">I end up seldom rereading books, I’m often tempted but then the guilt/panic kicks in of the reality of all the great books I haven’t even read once and I won’t even get to all those in one lifetime, so..…I almost always end up choosing a book I’ve never read. But occasionally the other voice in my head will insist, and (though not often) prevail. So here’s a reread of one of my formative science fiction novels, which blew my mind back in the day. And while I’m adjusting my rating to four stars (from the five of my memory), this holds up well. Most striking to me was all the rules Sturgeon ignored in writing this.<br /><br />-Show, don’t tell? Feh. Most of the book is related either in dialogue or through a character’s inner thoughts. And a central character who dies, the reader finds out a couple years after the event when another key character informs someone else, as though, “oh yeah, and then this happened.”<br /><br />-Science fiction published 1953, so action packed, yes? Not so much. <i>More Than Human</i> involves the burgeoning of <i>homo gestalt</i>, possibly the next step in human evolution, so one might expect some taking over the world vibe, supplanting humanity in certain major institutions, but no. There’s a section in the middle involving the military in a minor key sort of way, but really as just a means to an end. The six people who <i>blesh</i> as homo gestalt mostly keep to themselves in middle of nowhere locations.<br /><br />-The book opens with a sequence that plays out like an Angela Carter fairy tale riff, two young girls more or less imprisoned by their sincerely twisted father, and an attempted rescue by Lone, the early locus of the story. Which fails. It’s a gorgeous sequence, and atypical of the rest of the novel.<br /><br />The book seems structured to be almost deliberately frustrating and off-kilter. A major chunk of exposition is related by a character talking to a psychiatrist. Focus is ever changing, expected confrontations often don’t materialize. There are several children who at first might recall <i>Village of the Damned</i> in their creepy-disturbed affect, but you soon side with them over the adults they have to deal with. The book is always taking the scenic route, yet comes in at a lean 188 pages. Recommended, just leave your expectations at the door. Oh, and Lone, the idiot savant who for awhile comes closest to a main character, fixes his adopted father’s tractor by devising an anti-gravity device. As you do.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1563682171928857556" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

